<p>The Pettit test, i.e., a rank-based and distribution-free test, is commonly used to identify the date of a change point in a time series [
 <xref rid="B20-ijerph-17-02563" ref-type="bibr">20</xref>,
 <xref rid="B21-ijerph-17-02563" ref-type="bibr">21</xref>,
 <xref rid="B22-ijerph-17-02563" ref-type="bibr">22</xref>]. For the sequence of random variable (
 <italic>x</italic>
 <sub>1</sub>, 
 <italic>x</italic>
 <sub>2</sub>, …, 
 <italic>x
  <sub>n</sub>
 </italic>) with a change point at τ, the common distribution function for 
 <italic>x
  <sub>t</sub>
 </italic> (
 <italic>t</italic> = 1, 2, …, 
 <italic>τ</italic>) is different from that for 
 <italic>x
  <sub>t</sub>
 </italic> (
 <italic>t</italic> = 
 <italic>τ</italic> + 1, 
 <italic>τ</italic> + 2, …, 
 <italic>n</italic>). The null hypothesis, H
 <sub>0</sub>, for this test is that no change or 
 <italic>τ</italic> = 
 <italic>n</italic> is tested against the alternative hypothesis that change or 1 ≤ 
 <italic>τ</italic> &lt; 
 <italic>n</italic> by using the statistic 
 <italic>K
  <sub>n</sub>
 </italic>, whose form can be described as 
 <disp-formula>
  <italic>Kn</italic> = 
  <italic>Max</italic>|
  <italic>U
   <sub>t</sub>
  </italic>,
  <italic>
   <sub>n</sub>
  </italic>|, 1 ≤ 
  <italic>τ</italic> ≤ 
  <italic>n</italic>
  <label>(5)</label>
 </disp-formula> where 
 <disp-formula id="FD5-ijerph-17-02563">
  <label>(6)</label>
  <math id="mm6">
   <mrow>
    <mrow>
     <msub>
      <mi>U</mi>
      <mrow>
       <mi>t</mi>
       <mo>−</mo>
       <mi>n</mi>
      </mrow>
     </msub>
     <mo>=</mo>
     <munderover>
